                        <p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re putting up the virtual library and I would love to add this to the collection we&rsquo;re beginning to create,&rdquo; Widmer said. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m hoping through the magic of the Internet to see it soon. We&rsquo;re trying to raise awareness of Haiti&rsquo;s rich history at a time when the world is focused on their poverty. By seeing how far they&rsquo;ve come and how many obstacles they&rsquo;ve overcome, it helps to inspire us to help them in their hour of need.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Although the discovery has been kept relatively private, Gaffield said the reactions she has received have been enthusiastic.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We haven&rsquo;t talked to many people about this, but the reaction we&rsquo;ve gotten has been really positive,&rdquo; Gaffield said. &ldquo;One of the first people that I talked to when I got back was a librarian and archivist from Haiti, and he was just overjoyed with it. He was just so excited. But it&rsquo;s been mostly an internal thing. [Duke] is a very supportive place for research and a find like this.&rdquo;</p>

